      <hedline>
        <hl1>To End the Conflict in Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marc Sommers letter on Makau Mutua's Aug 30 article opposes call for partition of Tutsi and Hutu in Rwanda and Burundi</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Makau Mutua (Op-Ed, Aug. 30) suggests that Hutu and Tutsi can neither live nor rule together, but in post-genocide Rwanda, they do. He presumes that ''large population transfers'' would be both peaceful and appropriate. But destroying people's ties to their land, culture and country would further punish innocent people and open up still more opportunities for extremists to destabilize the region.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Makau Mutua (Op-Ed, Aug. 30) suggests that Hutu and Tutsi can neither live nor rule together, but in post-genocide Rwanda, they do. He presumes that ''large population transfers'' would be both peaceful and appropriate. But destroying people's ties to their land, culture and country would further punish innocent people and open up still more opportunities for extremists to destabilize the region.</p>
        <p>He also presumes that Hutu and Tutsi identities supersede all others, even Burundian and Rwandan national identities, which are vital to people in both countries. Finally, Mr. Mutua overlooks nonethnic factors contributing to central African violence, among them land shortages, poverty and the misguided policies of foreign governments and institutions.</p>
        <p>MARC SOMMERS  Boston, Aug. 30, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a research fellow, African Studies Center at Boston University.</p>
      </block>
